<h2>Additional Trip Cost Factors</h2>
<p>Don't forget to budget for:</p>
<ul>
    <li><strong>Tolls:</strong> Budget ₹2-5/km on national highways and expressways.</li>
    <li><strong>Parking:</strong> Hill stations and tourist spots often charge ₹50-200/day.</li>
    <li><strong>Fuel price variation:</strong> Petrol is cheaper in some states (MP, HP) and pricier in others (Maharashtra, Rajasthan).</li>
    <li><strong>Real-world mileage drop:</strong> AC usage, hill climbs, and traffic reduce mileage by 10-20% from highway estimates.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
<div class="faq-section">
    <div class="faq-item"><h3>How do I know my car's actual mileage?</h3><p>Fill tank completely, reset trip meter to zero, drive normally until the fuel warning light comes on, then fill the tank again. Note the fuel refuelled and km on the trip meter. Mileage = km / litres refuelled.</p></div>
    <div class="faq-item"><h3>Should I add AC usage to fuel cost estimate?</h3><p>Yes. AC reduces mileage by 10-15% in city driving and 5-10% on highways. If you'll be driving in summer heat with AC on, use 90% of your rated mileage in calculations.</p></div>
    <div class="faq-item"><h3>How do I split fuel costs fairly for carpooling?</h3><p>Total fuel cost / number of passengers (including driver) = equal split. If the driver is going anyway, some groups exclude the driver from payment. Agree on the method before the trip!</p></div>
</div>

